04848nam a22007335i 9780691187730DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911877307 a10.1515/97806911877302doi  a(DE-B1597)501839  a(OCoLC)1076406946  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBT153.M6bS29 2002eb 7aREL0150002bisacsh 7aREL0400602bisacsh04a291.2/1142231 aSchäfer, Peter, eauthor.10aMirror of His Beauty :bFeminine Images of God from the Bible to the Early Kabbalah /cPeter Schäfer. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2002  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJews, Christians, and Muslims from the Ancient to the Modern World00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFIGURES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: From the Bible to the Bahir -- tChapter 1. Lady Wisdom -- tChapter 2. Philo's Wisdom -- tChapter 3. The Gnostic Drama -- tChapter 4. The Rabbinic Shekhinah -- tChapter 5. The Shekhinah of the Philosophers -- tChapter 6. The Shekhinah in the Bahir -- tPART II. THE QUEST FOR ORIGINS -- tChapter 7. Gnosis -- tChapter 8. Christianity -- tChapter 9. Counter-Evidence: Mary and the Jews -- tChapter 10. How Much "Origins," Or: The Anxiety of Influence -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aIn this beautifully realized study, Peter Schäfer investigates the origins of a female manifestation of God in Jewish mysticism. The search itself is a fascinating exploration of the idea of a feminine divinity. And Schäfer's surprising but persuasive conclusions yield deeper understanding of the complex but frequently intimate relationship between Christianity and Judaism--and of the development of religious concepts more generally. Toward the end of the twelfth century, a small book titled the Bahir (Light) appeared in Provence. The first document of Judaism's emerging kabbalistic movement, it introduced a completely new view of God, one that included a divine potency that was essentially female. This female divinity was portrayed both as a mediator between Jews and God and as part of the Godhead itself. Examining Judaic history from the biblical Wisdom tradition to the Middle Ages, Schäfer finds some precedents for the Kabbalah's feminine divinity. But he cannot account for her forceful appearance in twelfth-century southern France without reference to the immediate Christian environment, particularly the flourishing veneration of the Virgin Mary. Indeed, twelfth-century Jews and Christians were simultaneously rediscovering the feminine as an aspect of the Godhead after having abandoned it in favor of either an abstract, disembodied God or an exclusively male one. In proposing that the medieval cult of Mary--rather than eastern Gnosticism--is the appropriate framework for understanding the feminine elements in Jewish mysticism, Mirror of His Beauty represents a sea change in Kabbalah and Jewish-Christian cultural studies. It shifts our attention from the Byzantine East to the Latin Christian West. And in contrast to histories that treat the development of Judaism and Christianity in isolation, it leads us to a fuller understanding of Jews and Christians living in proximity, aware of each other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aCabala. 0aFemininity of GodxBiblical teaching. 0aFemininity of GodxHistory of doctrines. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Kabbalah & Mysticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187730zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187730.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11S